'''Chemesthesis''' is defined as the chemical sensibility of the skin and mucous membranes. Chemesthetic sensations arise when [[chemical compound]]s activate [[Sensory receptor|receptor]]s associated with other [[sense]]s that mediate [[pain]], [[touch]], and [[Thermoception|thermal perception]]. These chemical-induced reactions do not fit into the traditional sense categories of [[taste]] and [[Olfaction|smell]]. Examples of chemesthetic sensations include the burn-like irritation from [[capsaicin]] and related compounds in foods like [[chili pepper]]s; the coolness of [[menthol]] in mouthwashes and topical analgesic creams; the stinging or tingling of [[carbonated beverages]] in the nose and mouth;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wise|first=Paul M.|last2=Wolf|first2=Madeline|last3=Thom|first3=Stephen R.|last4=Bryant|first4=Bruce|date=2013-08-21|title=The Influence of Bubbles on the Perception Carbonation Bite|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0071488|journal=PLOS ONE|language=en|volume=8|issue=8|pages=e71488|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0071488|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3749224|pmid=23990956|bibcode=2013PLoSO...871488W}}</ref> the tear-induction of cut onions;<ref name="Lawless">{{cite book |author= H. Lawless |author2= H. Heymann |last-author-amp= yes |title= Sensory Evaluation of Food |series= Chemical Senses, Vol. 2 , Principles and Practices | edition= 2nd |year= 2010 |publisher= Springer Science |location= New York |page= 41}}</ref> and the pungent, cough-inducing sensation in the back of the throat elicited by the [[oleocanthal]] in high-quality [[extra virgin olive oil]].<ref name="OleocanthalPaper">{{cite journal|vauthors=Peyrot des Gachons C, Uchida K, Bryant B, Shima A, Sperry JB, Dankulich-Nagrudny L, Tominaga M, Smith AB 3rd, Beauchamp GK, Breslin PA|title=Unusual pungency from extra-virgin olive oil is attributable to restricted spatial expression of the receptor of oleocanthal|journal=J Neurosci|date=19 January 2011|volume=31|issue=3|pages=999–1009|doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.1374-10.2011|pmid=21248124|url=http://www.jneurosci.org/content/31/3/999.long|accessdate=30 January 2017|pmc=3073417}}</ref> Some of these sensations may be referred to as spiciness, [[pungency]], or piquancy.
Chemesthetic sensations sometimes arise by direct chemical activation of ion channels on sensory nerve fibers, for example of [[transient receptor potential channel]]s including those of the [[TRPV]], [[TRPA (channel)|TRPA]] or [[TRPM]] subtypes. Alternatively, irritant chemicals may activate cells of the epithelium to release substances that indirectly activate the nerve fibers. The respiratory passages, including the nose and trachea, possess specialized cells called [[solitary chemosensory cells]]<ref name="Finger">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Finger TE, Böttger B, Hansen A |title=Solitary chemoreceptor cells in the nasal cavity serve as sentinels of respiration |journal=Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A |volume=100 |issue=15 |pages=8981–6 |year=2003 |pmid=12857948 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1531172100|postscript=.|pmc=166424|bibcode = 2003PNAS..100.8981F |display-authors=etal}}</ref> which release [[acetylcholine]]<ref name="Krasteva">{{Cite journal|vauthors=Krasteva G, Canning BJ, Hartmann P |title=Cholinergic chemosensory cells in the trachea regulate breathing |journal=Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A |volume=108 |issue=23 |pages=9478–83 |year=2011 |pmid=21606356 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1019418108|postscript=.|pmc=3111311|bibcode = 2011PNAS..108.9478K |display-authors=etal}}</ref> or other activators to excite nearby nerve fibers.
Because chemoresponsive nerve fibers are present in all types of skin, chemesthetic sensations can be aroused from anywhere on the body's surface as well as from mucosal surfaces in the nose, mouth, eyes, etc. Mucus membranes are generally more sensitive to chemesthetic stimuli because they lack the barrier function of [[Stratum corneum|cornified skin]].
Much of the chemesthetic flavor sensations are mediated by the [[trigeminal nerves]], which are relatively large and important nerves. Flavors that stimulate the trigeminal nerves are therefore important - for example, carbon dioxide is the trigeminal stimulant in carbonated beverages.<ref name="Lawless" />
